            <h2><strong> Preservation and fossilization</strong></h2>
            <p>The process of fossilization is complex and the outcome is determined by a variety of physical, chemical and biological factors.  Broadly speaking however, there are two special conditions that determine the potential of preservation; possesion of hard parts and burial speed.</p>  
            </br>
            <p>The preservation of soft parts is rare as they are often destroyed by scavengers or decomposed by bacteria, therefore the remaining evidence of them is little to non-existent in the geologic record.  That said, rare occasions do happen where the entire body of an animal is preserved such as when insects are trapped in amber or when mammoths are frozen in ice.</p>
            </br>
            <h4> <strong>Some forms of fossilization are: </strong></h4>
            <ul>
              <li><p> Permineralization: Occurs when ground water seeps into the pores or cavities of an organism filling it with rock forming minerals (silica, calcite, pyrite...). </p></li>
              <li><p> Replacement: Occurs when the hard and sometimes even soft parts of an organism dissolves and is replaced by minerals. </p></li>
              <li><p> Recrystallization: Occurs when the original mineralogy of an organism transforms into a more stable mineral.  This process often results in the destruction of the organism’s internal structure. </p></li>
              <li><p> Trace fossils:  Refers to the preservation of organism activity such as fossilized burrows, tooth marks and footprints. </p></li>
              <li><p> Molds:  Fossilized impressions of an organism. </p></li>
              <li><p> Casts: Occurs when molds are filled with material resulting in a replica of the organism's external form. </p></li>
              <li><p> Coprolites: The preserved fecal matter left behind by animals. </p></li>
            
            </ul>
            </br>
            <h4> <strong>Bias on the fossil record </strong></h4>
            <p> As fossilization favors the preservation of organisms with hard parts, the fossil record shows a distorted view of ancient life with a bias for organisms with hard parts.  For instance, insects represent the most abundant type of organisms, but as they do not have hard parts, the percentage of fossil insect population represented by the fossil record is below 1%.  However, even organisms with hard parts are prone to post-mortem destruction which favors organisms that live in an environment that can provide ease of burial.  The chemical and biologic destruction of shell material is another way in which the record fossil may be biased.  Because of the mechanical, chemical and biological forces that may alter the original composition of the ancient organism community, the fossil record must be viewed as a biased and atypical of life at any period of time.</p>
          </div>
